00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:48,500
but you can think of

548
00:25:48,500 --> 00:25:50,000
it as an elementary quantum mechanics.

549
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:54,000
You calculate a Feynman diagram.

550
00:25:54,000 --> 00:26:00,000
You calculate a Feynman diagram.

551
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:04,000
You can just think of it as elementary quantum mechanics.

552
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:06,000
This gives you a term in the Hamiltonian,

553
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:09,000
which takes the Higgs boson to a pair of particles,

554
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:11,000
and it just gives you the transition amplitude,

555
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:13,000
which you square.

556
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:14,000
And once you've squared it,

557
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:15,500
you integrate it or sum

558
00:26:15,500 --> 00:26:17,000
it over all the final states.

559
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:20,000
And that's the decay rate.

560
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:23,500
It's a standard calculation that

561
00:26:23,500 --> 00:26:27,000
is basically a Feynman diagram.

562
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:30,000
If you like, this gives you the amplitude.

563
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:34,000
You square the amplitude to get the decay rate.

564
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:36,000
Squaring the amplitude, you can just do

565
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:39,000
by putting this right on top of itself like that.

566
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:42,000
Here the amplitude is squared.

567
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:44,000
And that becomes a Feynman diagram.

568
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:47,000
You calculate the Feynman diagram by Feynman's rules.

569
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:48,500
One of the things that comes

570
00:26:48,500 --> 00:26:50,000
out of it is the decay rate.

571
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:56,000
But this is more than we're going to do here.

572
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:01,000
That's what we have to do.

573
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:04,000
So it's a very, very definite calculation

574
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:09,000
within standard quantum field theory.

575
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:11,000
And it's the kind of calculation

576
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:13,000
we've been doing since the 1930s.

577
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:16,000
So it's quite well known.

578
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:18,500
The only things that you have

579
00:27:18,500 --> 00:27:20,000
to put in, which are new,

580
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:22,000
are the values of these coupling constants,

581
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:26,000
masses of particles, and so forth.

582
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:31,000
Okay, so that was the masses of fermions,

583
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:35,000
the masses of the Z and W bosons,

584
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:39,000
all of them being proportional to this constant F.

585
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:45,000
Why don't we talk about the Higgs itself?

586
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:47,000
Why don't we talk about

587
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:49,000
the dynamics of the Higgs boson?

588
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:04,000
The dynamics is really all contained

589
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:08,000
in this Mexican hat potential.

590
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:10,000
The minimum of the Mexican hat potential

591
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:12,000
tells you how much the field is shifted,

592
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:14,000
and it tells you what F is.

593
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:19,000
You can make up different potentials that have this shape.

594
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:23,500
There's a favorite one which

595
00:28:23,500 --> 00:28:28,000
actually has some important theoretical significance.

596
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:31,000
And it goes as follows.

597
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:34,000
Let's go to the origin over here.

598
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:36,500
At the origin, the Higgs potential

599
00:28:36,500 --> 00:28:39,000
is a sort of upside-down parabola.

600
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:42,000
Let's forget what it does far from the origin.

601
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:44,000
Let's just concentrate on near the origin.

602
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:48,000
An upside-down parabola means something like minus,

603
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:53,000
let's call it mu squared, phi squared.

604
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:58,000
And it's traditional to put a 2 in here.

605
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:01,000
It's just traditional.

606
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:04,000
Minus because it's an upside-down parabola.

607
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:07,000
Remember, if it was plus mu squared, phi squared,

608
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:10,000
what would you call this term?

609
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:11,500
You would call this term

610
00:29:11,500 --> 00:29:13,000
the mass of the Higgs boson.

611
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:16,000
You would call mu the mass of the Higgs boson.

612
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:18,000
Or you would really call mu squared the

613
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:20,000
square of the mass of the Higgs boson.

614
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:24,000
Making it negative is a little bit weird.

615
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:26,000
It's as if there was an

616
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:28,000
imaginary mass for the Higgs boson.

617
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:30,000
But don't worry, there's nothing wrong with this.

618
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:31,500
It's perfectly okay to have

619
00:29:31,500 --> 00:29:33,000
a potential which is upside-down.

620
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:37,000
The only thing which is unusual about it

621
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:39,500
is putting the field at the

622
00:29:39,500 --> 00:29:42,000
origin is not a stable position.

623
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:46,000
It tends to roll off and roll down the hill.

624
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:49,000
Whereas if the mass term was positive,

625
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:53,000
it would oscillate about the central position here.

626
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:57,000
So the field does not oscillate about the top

627
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:00,000
because of this minus phi squared.

628
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:02,000
Now, if all you have is minus phi squared,

629
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:05,000
it would just go down and down and down,

630
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:08,000
and the field would just run away to infinity.

631
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:10,000
There would be no ground state to the system.

632
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:12,000
There would be no vacuum.

633
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:14,000
If the vacuum is the state of lowest energy,

634
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:16,000
there would be no state of lowest energy.

635
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:18,000
So we've got to put in something

636
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:21,000
to keep it from running away to infinity.

637
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:24,000
We better put in something to turn it up.

638
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:29,000
The simplest thing to turn it up is plus lambda,

639
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:31,000
where lambda is just a number,

640
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:33,000
a pure number,

641
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:38,000
times phi to the fourth.

642
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:40,000
Why do I want to put in phi?

643
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:41,000
Why not the phi cubed,

644
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:43,000
or phi to the fifth?

645
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:45,000
Why not odd powers?

646
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:47,000
Because we want to keep it symmetric on both sides.

647
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:50,000
This was an important aspect of this potential,

648
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:54,000
was to keep it nice and symmetric.

649
00:30:54,000 --> 00:30:57,000
So phi to the fourth is symmetric.

650
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:00,000
Phi cubed is not.

651
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:02,000
This is the next thing you can put in.

652
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:03,500
You can put in all sorts

653
00:31:03,500 --> 00:31:05,000
of things to higher powers here.

654
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:07,000
They're not so important.

655
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:09,000
The most important one is phi to the fourth

656
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:11,000
and expanding the potential and the mass.

657
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:13,000
So it's just a number.

658
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:15,000
It's not a power series.

659
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:17,000
You can put in more,

660
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:19,000
but this is the most important thing.

661
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:20,500
And in fact, it's also traditional

662
00:31:20,500 --> 00:31:22,000
to put a four over here.

663
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:24,000
You'll see why in a moment.

664
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:26,000
A two over here and a four over here.

665
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:28,000
What is this number?

666
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:31,000
This number is called a quartic coupling constant.

667
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:34,000
Quartic because it has phi to the fourth.

668
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:36,000
It is dimensionless.

669
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:39,000
It's a pure number.

670
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:42,000
And what we know about that pure number,

671
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:45,000
not from direct experimental evidence,

672
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:48,000
but from a lot of indirect evidence,

673
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:50,000
and what we know about that number

674
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:54,000
from somewhat indirect properties of weak interactions,

675
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:57,000
is that it's small,

676
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:00,000
but not absurdly small.

677
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:02,000
Probably about 1%,

678
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:04,000
probably about

679
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:07,000
1.01 or something like that.

680
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:08,000
So it's a number.

681
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:10,000
It's not 10 to the minus 20.

682
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:11,000
It's not 10 to the

683
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:12,000
minus 15 or anything like that.

684
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:13,500
So just think of it as a

685
00:32:13,500 --> 00:32:15,000
number for the moment of order one.

686
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:17,000
It's also dimensionless.

687
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:19,000
Mu is not dimensionless.

688
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:22,000
It has units of a mass.

689
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:25,000
Okay, now let's try to find out what f is.

690
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:27,000
f is dimensionless.

691
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:29,000
So if you look at the equation,

692
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:30,500
you can see that the

693
00:32:30,500 --> 00:32:32,000
number of units of a mass

694
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:34,000
is not dimensionless.

695
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:36,000
It's not dimensionless.

696
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:38,000
It's not dimensionless.

697
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:40,000
So what we're going to do is

698
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:42,000
we're going to take the position at the minimum here.

699
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:44,000
All we have to do is

700
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:46,000
minimize this with respect to phi.

701
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:47,500
We cooked it up so

702
00:32:47,500 --> 00:32:49,000
that it would have a minimum.

703
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:52,000
A rapidly falling quadratic term,

704
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:54,000
and then taken over by,

705
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:56,000
incidentally, near the origin,

706
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:58,000
this is smaller than this, right?

707
00:32:58,000 --> 00:32:59,500
Phi to the fourth is smaller

708
00:32:59,500 --> 00:33:01,000
than phi squared near the origin.

709
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:04,000
So this has not got much effect near the origin.

710
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:06,000
It picks up steam

711
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:08,000
and eventually becomes much bigger than phi squared.

712
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:10,000
So we're going to go to large phi.

713
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:11,000
So that turns it back up.

714
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:12,000
That's the logic.

715
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:15,000
Okay, let's just find the minimum of phi.

716
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:17,000
Sorry, the minimum of v

717
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:21,000
with respect to phi,

718
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:22,500
and that will tell us

719
00:33:22,500 --> 00:33:24,000
how much the field gets shifted.

720
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:26,000
All right, that's easy.

721
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:28,000
We just differentiate with respect to phi.

722
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:31,000
The derivative of phi squared is 2 phi.

723
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:32,000
That eats up this 2 down here.

724
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:34,000
That's why I put the 2 down there.

725
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:36,000
Minus mu squared phi.

726
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:38,000
This is the derivative of

727
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:40,000
v with respect to phi,

728
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:43,000
plus lambda,

729
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:45,000
which is a number of order of magnitude 1,

730
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:48,000
phi cubed.

731
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:50,000
I also put the 4 down here

732
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:53,000
so it would kill the 4 when I differentiated

733
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:55,000
with respect to phi to the fourth.

734
00:33:55,000 --> 00:33:57,000
And we set that equal to 0.

735
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:06,000
All right, now we can divide by phi.

736
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:09,000
We divide by phi.

737
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:11,000
Make this phi squared.

738
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:15,000
And what do we get?

739
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:17,000
We get phi squared

740
00:34:17,000 --> 00:34:19,000
is equal to mu squared

741
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:21,000
over lambda.

742
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:25,000
Again, lambda is an ordinary number.

743
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:29,000
Don't think of it as very big or very small.

744
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:33,000
This is the value of phi at the minimum.

745
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:35,000
It's also called f.

746
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:39,000
It's also the shift of the field, f.

747
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:43,000
And so f squared

748
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:47,000
becomes mu squared over lambda.

749
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:49,000
Again, I emphasize,

750
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:52,000
lambda is not the interesting number here.

751
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:55,000
It's the common garden variety number

752
00:34:55,000 --> 00:34:58,000
like 1 or a tenth or a hundredth

753
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:00,000
or something like that.

754
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:02,000
It's not very big, that's for sure.

755
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:04,000
Okay.

756
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:08,000
So, f is controlled by mu.

757
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:12,000
f is also approximately the mass

758
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:15,000
of the z and the w boson.

759
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:18,000
It's also the thing which comes into the mass

760
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:20,000
of the fermions.

761
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:22,000
Where are they?

762
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:25,000
All of the particles have masses proportional to f.

763
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:28,000
Let's take the square root of this.

764
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:33,000
So it's mu or f or mu.

765
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:36,000
Which is the controlling factor

766
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:39,000
which controls all of these masses.

767
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:40,000
All of them.

768
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:41,500
All the masses of all

769
00:35:41,500 --> 00:35:43,000
the particles that we know about.

770
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:46,000
Okay, that raises an interesting question.

771
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:51,000
Why are all of the particles that we know about

772
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:55,000
controlled by the same phenomenon,

773
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:57,000
namely f?

774
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:00,000
Why aren't there particles which have masses

775
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:03,000
without spontaneous symmetry breaking?

776
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:06,000
We can certainly make up a theory of such particles.

777
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:09,000
For example, just make up a particle

778
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:12,000
whose left-handed and right-handed components

779
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:15,000
both have weak charge.

780
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:16,500
Then we have no reason

781
00:36:16,500 --> 00:36:18,000
to put this phi in there.

782
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:20,000
We wouldn't put the phi in there.

783
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:21,500
And you could put any mass

784
00:36:21,500 --> 00:36:23,000
that you like in front of it.

785
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:25,000
And it's perfectly symmetric.

786
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:27,000
So, if there was a particle

787
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:30,000
which was

788
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:33,000
whose left- and right-handed

789
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:36,000
components both interacted with the weak interactions

790
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:38,000
the same way,

791
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:40,000
they could have a mass

792
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:42,000
which was not proportional to f.

793
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:44,000
All kinds of other particles could all

794
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:47,000
particles that don't have any weak interactions at all,

795
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:49,000
if there were such particles,

796
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:54,000
could have masses which are not controlled by f.

797
00:36:54,000 --> 00:36:57,000
The general thinking which we'll come to,

798
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:00,000
and I'll explain why this is the general thinking,

799
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:03,000
is that the natural mass scale for particle physics

800
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:05,000
is enormous.

801
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:07,000
Much, much higher

802
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:11,000
than the masses of any of the ordinary elementary particles.

803
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:15,000
It's thought that only this one number, f,

804
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:18,000
is the unusual number in physics,

805
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:21,000
the very, very small mass scale,

806
00:37:21,000 --> 00:37:24,000
whose origins are at present unknown.

807
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:27,000
But what is thought, and I'll explain as we,

808
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:29,000
well, this quarter, next quarter,

809
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:32,000
various points,

810
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:38,000
the idea that really the only mass parameter,

811
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:42,000
the only small mass parameter in nature,

812
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:45,000
is this f here.

813
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:47,000
And those particles,

814
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:52,000
which by necessity have to have masses proportional to f,

815
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:53,000
why?

816
00:37:53,000 --> 00:37:56,000
Because it's in the nature of their mathematics

817
00:37:56,000 --> 00:37:58,000
that they would have to be massless

818
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:01,000
if there was no shift of f.

819
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:02,000
Only those particles

820
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:06,000
are light enough to have been detected at present.

821
