1095
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:13,000
so if this is plus,

1096
00:50:13,000 --> 00:50:16,000
an opposite charge cloud is found around it,

1097
00:50:16,000 --> 00:50:19,000
it completely discharges it,

1098
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:24,000
so that outside there's no electric field at all,

1099
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:27,000
and no more reason for the charges to flow.

1100
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:29,500
Now these charges are of

1101
00:50:29,500 --> 00:50:32,000
course bound to the positive charge,

1102
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:33,000
they're bound to it,

1103
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:36,000
and the whole thing forms a neutral structure.

1104
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:39,000
If you take another negative charge over here,

1105
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:42,000
exactly the opposite thing will happen to it,

1106
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:45,000
it will create some plus charge around it,

1107
00:50:45,000 --> 00:50:47,000
same deal,

1108
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:50,000
the charges will flow until it's completely neutralized,

1109
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:52,000
and then you take these two charges,

1110
00:50:52,000 --> 00:50:55,000
you thought you had two charges to begin with,

1111
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:57,000
you evaluate or measure the

1112
00:50:57,000 --> 00:50:59,000
force between them at large distances,

1113
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:02,000
and you find out that there is none.

1114
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:08,000
So, the charge that you put in to begin with

1115
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:09,500
is not the experimental charge

1116
00:51:09,500 --> 00:51:11,000
at the end of the day,

1117
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:13,500
the experimental charge at the end of the

1118
00:51:13,500 --> 00:51:16,000
day in this case is just plain zero.

1119
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:20,000
Now what happens is you start moving the two charges,

1120
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:22,000
let's suppose they're really small,

1121
00:51:22,000 --> 00:51:25,000
and you start moving them closer and closer together.

1122
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:28,000
Is this screening?

1123
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:30,000
Screening.

1124
00:51:30,000 --> 00:51:32,000
This is device screening.

1125
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:37,000
Supposing these charges are really small,

1126
00:51:37,000 --> 00:51:38,500
in particular they're smaller than

1127
00:51:38,500 --> 00:51:40,000
the clouds around them that form.

1128
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:42,500
The clouds around them are controlled by

1129
00:51:42,500 --> 00:51:45,000
various properties of the metal and so forth,

1130
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:47,000
and the electrons moving in the metal,

1131
00:51:47,000 --> 00:51:50,000
and we imagine making these charges even smaller.

1132
00:51:50,000 --> 00:51:52,000
We bring them really close together.

1133
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:55,000
We bring them so close together that

1134
00:51:55,000 --> 00:51:58,000
the screening cloud can't get between them.

1135
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:02,000
Typically there's a scale for the screening cloud.

1136
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:05,500
It's controlled by the dynamics

1137
00:52:05,500 --> 00:52:09,000
of the electrons in the system,

1138
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:15,000
and the particles making up the screening cloud

1139
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:18,000
typically have a certain distance between them,

1140
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:22,000
and that distance controls the size of the screening cloud.

1141
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:23,500
When you bring these two

1142
00:52:23,500 --> 00:52:25,000
particles closer than the screening cloud,

1143
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:27,000
they're no longer screened.

1144
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:31,000
They actually feel each other's raw basic charge,

1145
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:34,000
and you see that there's a Coulomb force between them,

1146
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:37,000
which is the usual E squared over R.

1147
00:52:37,000 --> 00:52:38,000
Okay?

1148
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:40,000
So you could say then

1149
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:42,000
that the charge of the electron,

1150
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:45,000
or the charge of the particle in this case,

1151
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:49,000
is really a function of distance.

1152
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:51,000
In the case of the conductor,

1153
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:55,000
E of R is zero at very large R.

1154
00:52:55,000 --> 00:52:57,500
It's whatever the ordinary charge of

1155
00:52:57,500 --> 00:53:00,000
the particle is at very small r,

1156
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:02,000
and the force law, instead of

1157
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:04,000
being just plain E squared over R,

1158
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:07,000
has E squared of R divided by R squared.

1159
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:10,000
This is just a definition of

1160
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:12,000
E squared of R, if you like.

1161
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:13,500
I don't put anything new into it

1162
00:53:13,500 --> 00:53:15,000
by calling it E squared of R,

1163
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:19,000
but it does have a nice sound to it.

1164
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:21,000
It's called the running charge.

1165
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:25,000
Running is a function of distance between them.

1166
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:28,000
Okay, now what happens if you

1167
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:31,000
have something less extreme than a conductor?

1168
00:53:31,000 --> 00:53:33,000
For example, a dielectric.

1169
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:36,000
A dielectric, if you like, has electrons

1170
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:38,000
which are bound together.

1171
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:40,000
Electrons are bound to the atoms.

1172
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:42,000
Electrons are bound to the atoms,

1173
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:44,000
but they're free to shift a little bit.

1174
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:46,000
If you like, you can almost think

1175
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:48,000
of the electrons as being on springs,

1176
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:50,000
where the one end of the

1177
00:53:50,000 --> 00:53:52,000
spring the electron is attached to,

1178
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:57,000
the other end of the spring the ion,

1179
00:53:57,000 --> 00:54:01,000
the positively charged ion is attached.

1180
00:54:01,000 --> 00:54:05,000
And ordinarily, the electron moves symmetrically,

1181
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:06,000
vibrates symmetrically.

1182
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:08,000
Of course, this is not really a good picture

1183
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:11,000
of an atom, but it's good enough for our purposes.

1184
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:14,000
The electron oscillates and vibrates back and forth

1185
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:16,000
symmetrically about the atom.

1186
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:18,500
So on the average, the dipole

1187
00:54:18,500 --> 00:54:21,000
moment of the atom is zero.

1188
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:24,000
But now you put the atom into an electric field,

1189
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:26,500
and what happens is the

1190
00:54:26,500 --> 00:54:29,000
electron cloud shifts a little bit.

1191
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:36,000
It shifts a little bit, leaving a dipole left over.

1192
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:38,000
The current doesn't flow.

1193
00:54:38,000 --> 00:54:40,000
The charge just shifts a little bit

1194
00:54:40,000 --> 00:54:44,000
because they're bound to the atoms.

1195
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:48,500
Okay, so now what happens if

1196
00:54:48,500 --> 00:54:53,000
you put a charge into a dielectric?

1197
00:54:53,000 --> 00:54:55,000
Well, a very similar phenomenon happens.

1198
00:54:55,000 --> 00:55:00,000
Let's suppose we put a minus charge in over here.

1199
00:55:00,000 --> 00:55:05,000
All the ions are heavy.

1200
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:07,000
They don't move very much.

1201
00:55:07,000 --> 00:55:08,500
But the electrons which are

1202
00:55:08,500 --> 00:55:10,000
bound to them by the springs

1203
00:55:10,000 --> 00:55:15,000
move out away from the central atom.

1204
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:16,000
What does that leave?

1205
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:18,000
That leaves a little bit of plus charge here.

1206
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:23,000
But it doesn't completely screen the charge.

1207
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:27,000
It screens some fraction of the charge.

1208
00:55:27,000 --> 00:55:28,500
So that if you look very,

1209
00:55:28,500 --> 00:55:30,000
very far away from the charged particle,

1210
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:34,000
you'll find that the field,

1211
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:37,000
the electric field is diminished by a certain fraction,

1212
00:55:37,000 --> 00:55:40,000
but it doesn't go to zero very far away.

1213
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:44,000
The fraction is controlled by the dielectric constant.

1214
00:55:44,000 --> 00:55:48,000
The dielectric constant will tell you what the screening is.

1215
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:51,000
So again, you'll find that a large separation,

1216
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:53,000
this plus charge and this minus charge,

1217
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:55,000
don't satisfy the expected Coulomb

1218
00:55:55,000 --> 00:55:57,000
law that you might have expected

1219
00:55:57,000 --> 00:55:59,000
from the actual, let's call it

1220
00:55:59,000 --> 00:56:01,000
the bare charge of these particles,

1221
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:04,000
but it's diminished by this,

1222
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:06,000
by this effect.

1223
00:56:06,000 --> 00:56:09,000
It's diminished, the Coulomb law is correct,

1224
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:12,000
but with a diminished value of the charge.

1225
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:14,000
So in this case, you would also have an

1226
00:56:14,000 --> 00:56:16,000
E squared of R or an E of R.

1227
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:19,000
Again, if you bring the charges very close together

1228
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:22,000
so that they're within the screening cloud,

1229
00:56:22,000 --> 00:56:25,000
then you feel the full strength of the bare charge.

1230
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:29,000
So again, E squared is a function of R.

1231
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:32,000
In this case, it wouldn't go to zero and infinity.

1232
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:34,000
It would just go to some constant,

1233
00:56:34,000 --> 00:56:37,000
a fraction of the original charge.

1234
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:40,000
Again, the concept of a running charge.

1235
00:56:40,000 --> 00:56:42,000
All right, now, exactly this phenomenon,

1236
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:44,000
it really is exactly this phenomenon,

1237
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:46,000
happens in quantum field theory.

1238
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:49,000
The origin of it is the pairs,

1239
00:56:49,000 --> 00:56:51,000
let's take quantum electrodynamics.

1240
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:53,000
In quantum electrodynamics,

1241
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:59,000
the vacuum is full of electron-positron pairs.

1242
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:02,000
There are Feynman diagrams

1243
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:05,000
where electrons, positrons are created by photons,

1244
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:11,000
even just electron-positron loops with no photons,

1245
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:14,000
and they inhabit the vacuum, if you like.

1246
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:16,000
The other way you can think about it

1247
00:57:16,000 --> 00:57:18,000
is you can think about it

1248
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:20,000
in terms of Dirac's negative energy C.

1249
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:23,000
The vacuum is filled with this negative energy C.

1250
00:57:23,000 --> 00:57:25,500
Or you can imagine that there

1251
00:57:25,500 --> 00:57:28,000
are electron-positron pairs in the vacuum.

1252
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:31,000
What happens when an electric field comes along?

1253
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:34,000
The electric field will shift the positrons one way

1254
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:37,000
and shift the electrons the other way,

1255
00:57:37,000 --> 00:57:40,000
so that every little virtual pair,

1256
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:43,000
electron-positron pair, will become polarized.

1257
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:45,500
Polarized in exactly the same way that

1258
00:57:45,500 --> 00:57:48,000
atoms become polarized by an electric field.

1259
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:50,000
The plus charge is shifting one way,

1260
00:57:50,000 --> 00:57:52,000
the minus charge is shifting the other way.

1261
00:57:52,000 --> 00:57:53,500
That's what happens in the vacuum

1262
00:57:53,500 --> 00:57:55,000
when you put an electric field on.

1263
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:00,000
Okay, that's step number one.

1264
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:01,000
Step number two.

1265
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:04,500
Of course, you put in what you thought

1266
00:58:04,500 --> 00:58:08,000
was an original bare charge of magnitude E.

1267
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:11,000
The charges in the vacuum rearrange a little bit.

1268
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:14,000
The vacuum is basically a dielectric.

1269
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:15,000
It's basically a dielectric.

1270
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:17,000
The charges shift a little bit,

1271
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:20,000
and in such a way that negative charges

1272
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:23,000
are screened by a little bit of positive charge

1273
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:25,000
from these virtual pairs,

1274
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:27,500
and positive charges are screened by

1275
00:58:27,500 --> 00:58:30,000
a little bit of negative charge.

1276
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:33,500
The upshot is the charge

1277
00:58:33,500 --> 00:58:36,000
that's felt at a large distance

1278
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:39,000
is not the same as the numerical value

1279
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:42,000
of the charge that you put into the Lagrangian,

1280
00:58:42,000 --> 00:58:46,000
which is usually called the bare electric charge.

1281
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:49,000
But again, you start moving the

1282
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:52,000
electrons closer and closer to each other,

1283
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:55,500
and at some point they get closer

1284
00:58:55,500 --> 00:58:59,000
than the size of the screening cloud.

1285
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:02,000
But there's one difference in this case.

1286
00:59:02,000 --> 00:59:08,000
In this case, there is no set distance

1287
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:14,000
that the electron positrons tend to be separated by.

1288
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:17,500
The right statement is that the separation between

1289
00:59:17,500 --> 00:59:21,000
the electron positron pairs depends on their energy.

1290
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:24,500
The higher the energy of the

1291
00:59:24,500 --> 00:59:28,000
virtual pair, the closer they will be.

1292
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:31,000
So there will be electron

1293
00:59:31,000 --> 00:59:34,000
positron pairs which form relatively big,

1294
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:37,000
let's call them atoms, they're not atoms,

1295
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:40,000
but let's call them atomic neutral systems.

1296
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:42,000
There will be ones of

1297
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:44,000
higher virtual energy which are smaller,

1298
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:47,000
ones of yet higher virtual energy which are even smaller,

1299
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:51,000
ones which are higher energy which are even smaller.

1300
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:54,000
Okay, so what happens when you put the charge in?

1301
00:59:54,000 --> 00:59:57,000
And bring another charge closer and closer to it?

1302
00:59:57,000 --> 01:00:00,000
And bring another charge closer and closer and closer.

1303
01:00:00,000 --> 01:00:05,500
At first, you will bring them close enough that they'll

1304
01:00:05,500 --> 01:00:11,000
be within the distance of the low energy virtual pairs.

1305
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:14,000
The low energy virtual pairs will no

1306
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:17,000
longer be able to screen the charge,

1307
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:20,000
and so the charge will look a little bit smaller, sorry,

1308
01:00:20,000 --> 01:00:23,000
a little bit bigger than it would when they were far apart.

1309
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:24,500
Why? When they were far

1310
01:00:24,500 --> 01:00:26,000
apart, they were completely screened,

1311
01:00:26,000 --> 01:00:28,000
not completely screened, but they were

1312
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:30,000
screened by all possible virtual pairs.

1313
01:00:30,000 --> 01:00:32,000
You bring them a little bit

1314
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:34,000
closer, the low energy virtual pairs,

1315
01:00:34,000 --> 01:00:37,500
which had a large separation between them,

1316
01:00:37,500 --> 01:00:41,000
you bring the charges closer than that,

1317
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:42,500
and the low energy virtual pairs

1318
01:00:42,500 --> 01:00:44,000
are no longer important in screening.

1319
01:00:44,000 --> 01:00:46,000
But the higher energy virtual

1320
01:00:46,000 --> 01:00:48,000
pairs are still doing some screening.

1321
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:53,000
You bring them a little closer,

1322
01:00:53,000 --> 01:00:55,000
the higher energy pairs are still doing some screening.

1323
01:00:56,000 --> 01:00:58,000
The higher energy virtual pairs fall out

1324
01:00:58,000 --> 01:01:00,000
of the equation because they're too far apart,

1325
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:02,000
and yet higher energy ones are still there.

1326
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:06,500
The effect is that that E squared of R is

1327
01:01:06,500 --> 01:01:11,000
a function which keeps changing and changing and changing with R.

1328
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:16,000
It doesn't stop changing at some particular small distance.

1329
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:19,000
The closer and closer you bring the electron

1330
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:22,000
together, the larger the charge will appear to be.

1331
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:24,000
So if you were to plot,

1332
01:01:24,000 --> 01:01:26,000
the virtue of the fact that there are

1333
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:28,000
pairs of every possible energy in the vacuum.

1334
01:01:28,000 --> 01:01:36,000
So if you were to plot the electric charge

1335
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:43,000
as a function of radial separation,

1336
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:48,000
let's plot it as a function of inverse radial separation.

1337
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:51,000
Inverse radial separation is like energy.

1338
01:01:51,000 --> 01:01:54,000
The closer things are together, the higher their energy.

1339
01:01:54,000 --> 01:02:01,000
So let's plot it as a function of inverse separation,

1340
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:03,500
one over R, which is also

1341
01:02:03,500 --> 01:02:06,000
related to energy or momentum or whatever.

1342
01:02:06,000 --> 01:02:13,000
Then the electric charge that you'll see will increase.

1343
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:16,000
It'll increase very slowly, in fact.

1344
01:02:16,000 --> 01:02:18,000
It's a very slow logarithmic increase.

1345
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:20,000
It doesn't increase rapidly.

1346
01:02:20,000 --> 01:02:23,000
That's why it's very hard to see in an experiment.

1347
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:26,500
It's a logarithmic gradual increase of

1348
01:02:26,500 --> 01:02:29,000
the size of an electric charge

1349
01:02:29,000 --> 01:02:33,000
as you study smaller and smaller distance phenomenon.

1350
01:02:33,000 --> 01:02:35,000
It's also true, for example,

1351
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:38,000
electric charge comes into

1352
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:41,000
calculations of scattering of electrons.

1353
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:45,000
If you scatter electrons at a low energy,

1354
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:48,000
they only get within a certain distance of each other.

